frameDefinitions: A Billing_authority communicates in written form that the Debtor owes the Owed_party (often the same as the Billing_authority) some amount of Money for certain Goods (including services) provided by the Owed_party or to clear a debt for a Bad_action by the Debtor against the Owed_party.
This frame covers entities which are prototypically conceived of and created to fulfill the function of containing--i.e.
A quantity, the Numerator, can be understood in terms of how it relates to another quantity, the Denominator; the comparison of these two numbers is called the Rate.
A Cognizer faces a choice on some Issue.
A Product is offered by a Seller at a particular Price such that some total cost for the Buyer in the transaction is a multiple of the Price.
An Agent causes Air to move in a direction, usually specifying either in or out of the body.
frameExamples: I'm not paying the high interest <t>rates</t>.
Dave Hayes <t>wavered</t> about moving to California because so many of his friends are in Baltimore.
listRoleDefinitions: The person (or organization) that owes the <fen>Owed_party</fen>.
The role <fen>Goods</fen> is anything (including labor or time, for example) which is exchanged for <fen>Money</fen> in a transaction.
<fen>Money</fen> is the thing given in exchange for <fen>Goods</fen> in a transaction, or as recompense for the <fen>Bad_action</fen>.
In some cases, price or payment is described per unit of <fen>Goods</fen>.

The <fen>Owed_party</fen> expects a specific amount of <fen>Money</fen> from the <fen>Debtor</fen>, either because the <fen>Debtor</fen> received <fen>Goods</fen> or because the <fen>Debtor</fen> performed a Bad_action against the Owed_party.
The individual who communicates to the <fen>Debtor</fen> the <fen>Money</fen> that they owe.

An earlier action by the <fen>Debtor</fen> causing harm (directly or indirectly) to the <fen>Owed_party</fen>, for which the <fen>Owed_party</fen> expects compensation, and therefore bills the <fen>Debtor</fen>.
When the event occurs.
Where the event takes place.
<fen>Container</fen> is an object which is conventionally used as a container.  Target words in this frame are tagged with this frame element.
The number which represents the relative quantities of the <fen>Numerator</fen> and the <fen>Denominator</fen>.
Identifies the quantity whose magnitude is determined relative to the <fen>Denominator</fen>.
The set of things to which the <fen>Rate</fen> pertains.
The quantity whose magnitude is determined relative to the <fen>Numerator</fen>.
The <fen>Cognizer</fen> is the person who repeatedly changes their mind about which of the <fen>Options</fen> to choose.
The <fen>Options</fen> are the alternative courses of action or the alternative physical or concrete entities that the <fen>Cognizer</fen> can choose from.
The <fen>Issue</fen> is a question about a course of action or a choice between items.

When there is an explicitly separate construal of the <fen>Options</fen>, <fen>Option_1</fen> is the first-mentioned alternative, typically in the form of a from-PP. When it is clear that  the <fen>Cognizer</fen> actually acted on their choice, <fen>Option_1</fen> is the alternative they embraced first before pursuing <fen>Option_2</fen>.

When there is an explicitly separate construal of the <fen>Options</fen>, <fen>Option_2</fen> is the second-mentioned alternative, typically in the form of a to-PP. When it is clear that  the <fen>Cognizer</fen> actually acted on their choice, <fen>Option_2</fen> is the alternative they embraced after abandoning <fen>Option_1</fen>.
This role denotes the <fen>Time</fen> interval during which the <fen>Cognizer</fen> keeps changing their mind about which of the <fen>Options</fen> to select.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Cognizer</fen> keeps changing their mind between the <fen>Options</fen> that present themselves.
A commodity, item, or service being sold by the <fen>Seller</fen> at a certain <fen>Price</fen>.
The amount of money that the <fen>Seller</fen> charges the <fen>Buyer</fen> for a <fen>Product</fen>.
The <fen>Agent</fen>'s breathing causes the motion of the <fen>Air</fen>.  <fen>Agent</fen> is generally the External Argument.
<fen>Air</fen> is the substance that the <fen>Agent</fen> causes to move.
The time at which breathing occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the breathing occurs.
